<p><b>Frederick Antony Ravi Kumar Zacharias</b> (born 1946) is an <a href="/wiki/India" title="India">Indian</a>-born, <a href="/wiki/Canada" title="Canada">Canadian</a>-<a href="/wiki/United_States" title="United States">American</a> <a href="/wiki/Evangelicalism" title="Evangelicalism">evangelical</a> <a href="/wiki/Christianity" title="Christianity">Christian</a> <a href="/wiki/Christian_apologetics" title="Christian apologetics">apologist</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Evangelism" title="Evangelism">evangelist</a>. Zacharias is the author of numerous Christian books, including <a href="/wiki/Gold_Medallion_Book_Award" title="Gold Medallion Book Award" class="mw-redirect">Gold Medallion Book Award</a> winner <i>Can Man Live Without God?</i><sup id="cite_ref-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-0" title=""><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup> and bestsellers <i>Light in the Shadow of Jihad</i><sup id="cite_ref-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-1" title=""><span>[</span>2<span>]</span></a></sup> and <i>The Grand Weaver</i>.<sup id="cite_ref-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-2" title=""><span>[</span>3<span>]</span></a></sup> He is also president of Ravi Zacharias International Ministries, host of the radio programs <i>Let My People Think</i> and <i>Just Thinking</i> (heard weekly and daily, respectively, on Christian stations across the U.S.), and visiting professor at <a href="/wiki/Wycliffe_Hall,_Oxford" title="Wycliffe Hall, Oxford">Wycliffe Hall</a> of <a href="/wiki/University_of_Oxford" title="University of Oxford">Oxford</a>, where he teaches apologetics and evangelism.<sup id="cite_ref-Wycliffe_3-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Wycliffe-3" title=""><span>[</span>4<span>]</span></a></sup> Previously, Zacharias studied as a visiting scholar at <a href="/wiki/Cambridge_University" title="Cambridge University" class="mw-redirect">Cambridge University</a> and held the chair in Evangelism and Contemporary Thought at <a href="/wiki/Nyack_College" title="Nyack College">Alliance Theological Seminary</a> from 1981 to 1984.<sup id="cite_ref-4" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-4" title=""><span>[</span>5<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
